'''Cumin''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|juː|m|ɨ|n}} or {{IPAc-en|UK|ˈ|k|ʌ|m|ɨ|n}}, {{IPAc-en|US|ˈ|k|uː|m|ɨ|n}}; sometimes spelled '''cummin'''; '''''Cuminum cyminum''''') is a [[flowering plant]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Apiaceae]], native from the [[east Mediterranean]] to [[India]]. Its seeds (each one contained within a fruit, which is dried) are used in the [[cuisine]]s of many different cultures, in both whole and ground form.

==Etymology==
The English "cumin" derives from the [[Old English]] ''cymen'' (or [[Old French]] ''cumin''), from [[Latin]] ''cuminum'',<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059%3Aentry%3Dcuminum cuminum],

Charlton T. Lewis, Charles Short, ''A Latin Dictionary'', on Perseus Digital Library</ref> which is the [[Latinisation (literature)|latinisation]] of the [[Greek language|Greek]] κύμινον (''kuminon''),<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dku%2Fminon κύμινον], known as saunf or سونف in Pakistan.
Henry George Liddell, Sydey Tsui, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus Digital Library</ref> cognate with Hebrew כמון (''kammon'') and Arabic كمون (''kammun'').<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cumin cumin], Persian: Zeereh   زیره , Online Etymology Dictionary</ref> Forms of this word are attested in several ancient Semitic languages, including ''kamūnu'' in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]].<ref>"[http://www.premiumwanadoo.com/cuneiform.languages/dictionary/dosearch.php?searchkey=kam%26%23363%3Bnu&language=rawakkadian Kamūnu]." ''premiumwanadoo.com.''</ref> The ultimate source is the [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] word ''hi''.<ref>Anton Deimel, ''Orientalia'' Old Series 13 (1924) 330.</ref> The earliest attested form of the word κύμινον (''kuminon'') is the [[Mycenaean Greek]] ''ku-mi-no'', written in [[Linear B]] syllabic script.<ref>[http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ Palaeolexicon], Word study tool of ancient languages</ref>

