* Protein (g): 1.07

==Confusion with other spices==
[[File:Black Cumin.jpg|thumb|left|Black cumin seeds]]

Cumin is sometimes confused with [[caraway]] (''Carum carvi''), another [[umbelliferous]] spice. Cumin, though, is hotter to the taste, lighter in color, and larger. Many European languages do not distinguish clearly between the two. Many [[slavic languages|Slavic]] and [[Uralic languages]] refer to cumin as "[[Rome|Roman]] caraway". Examples include [[Czech language|Czech]]: ''kmín'' – caraway, ''římský kmín'' -cumin; [[Polish language|Polish]]: ''kminek'' – caraway, ''kmin rzymski'' – cumin; [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: ''kömény'' – caraway, ''római kömény'' – cumin.  [[Finnish language|Finnish]]: ''kumina'' – caraway, ''roomankumina'' – cumin, although sometimes also called ''juustokumina'', cheese caraway. In [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], caraway is called both ''karve'' and ''kummin''/''kømming'' while cumin is ''spisskummen'', from the word ''spise'', to eat. Similarly in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] and [[Danish language|Danish]], caraway is ''kummin''/''kommen'', while cumin is ''spiskummin''/''spidskommen''. In [[German language|German]], ''Kümmel'' stands for caraway and ''Kreuzkümmel'' denotes cumin. In [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]], caraway is ''kúmen'', while cumin is ''kúmín''. In [[Romanian language|Romanian]], ''chimen'' is caraway, while ''chimion'' is cumin.

The distantly related ''[[Bunium persicum]]'' and the unrelated ''[[Nigella sativa]]'' are both sometimes called black cumin (''q.v.'').

== Aroma profile ==
[[File:CuminEssOil.png|thumb|Cumin essential oil in clear glass vial]]

Cumin's distinctive flavor and strong, warm aroma are due to its [[essential oil]] content. Its main constituent [[aroma compounds]] are [[cuminaldehyde]] (a promising agent against [[alpha-synuclein]] aggregation) and [[cuminic alcohol]]. Other important aroma compounds of toasted cumin are the [[Substitution (chemistry)|substituted]] [[pyrazine]]s, 2-ethoxy-3-isopropylpyrazine, 2-methoxy-3-''sec''-butylpyrazine, and 2-methoxy-3-methylpyrazine. Other components include [[Terpinene|γ-terpinene]], [[safranal]], [[cymene|p-cymene]] and [[beta-Pinene|β-pinene]].<ref name=cceo>{{cite journal
